			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">(This is a story an old friend and I were workingon together, we lost touch and I just found this again - pls ignore any inconsistencies, it was a work in progress <img src="images/smiles/icon_lol.gif" alt="icon_lol.gif" border="0" />)
<br />

<br />
Love and Death - Nothing else is eternal 
<br />

<br />
CHAPTER ONE: Dark Lady (Simba)
<br />

<br />
Her eyes raked the land, her once hunting grounds and homeland, from the highest tower of the dark castle, nestled in the mountains.  Such a raw, rough, wild land offered an excellent cover and plenty of prey, if she could but leave the ruins.  But she could not.  No, now she could only use magick to entrance her prey to her.  Or if another too bold adventurer made way into her abode, seeking treasure.  For she could not leave the dark ruined castle, not since he had cursed her.  
<br />

<br />
Rage and something else flitted across her face.  If another had seen it they would have caught perhaps gladness or relief warring with her hunger and rage.  It was gone before she even felt it and her ire spewed forth.  Damnable Hunters!  She fumed for a bit then paused.  Perhaps if she turned one, a properly subserviant pet to hunt for her!  Yes, she could feast every night!  Yes, disappearances were common in these lands, many monsters, wild creatures, and other mishaps awaited the too bold adventurer.  
<br />

<br />
Chuckling throatily and raising her hood up to cover her features, she strode forward through empty halls and entered the Room of Pools, once cherished by her kin. Briefly the dark Lady glanced down, not intending to stop but the reflection mirrored on the still, oily magick water sent her tumbling back in time…
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">Silmesse Reahe’ was beautiful, breathtakingly so, even by elven standards. She was tall, taller than most human men, and well built, slender yet strength and muscle was apparent. A wild mass of raven locks curled down her back, almost to her knees, with strands of pure silver making her hair seem as a night sky, dotted by stars. Slightly tilted, feline eyes flashed a clear green and her full lips were always smiling. When she reached a fair skinned hand back to pat a random tress back, it revealed a pointed ear.
<br />

<br />
Silmesse, or in mortal tongue, Starlight, was intelligent, benevolent, and wise. Tomorrow she would take the reins and become the elven nation’s LoreWielder, the one who was gifted by the Elders to hold all the secrets of the elf nation. She was trained in all arts, a warrior, a healer, a bard, and a sorceress. Every elfmaid was trained from birth with this in mind, so all had some knowledge, but every 100 years, only one was chosen to accept the Elder’s knowledge. The one chosen was not known until the day before the ritual when the Council of Teachers named her. The ceremony took place at midnight when the Shades would visit Silme and transfer eons of knowledge, from healing to war to magick, to her mind. And so, she sat, in the Room of Pools, by the center one, called Llyias a’ Riel, waiting the appointed hour.
<br />

<br />
It was lonely in the castle. For years this place had been solely for the Shades to inhabit, and on special occasions, other elves, like Silme. Great butchery had occurred here when the Slayer, whom the elves had hunted passionately, had come with his minions down and feasted on the elvenfolk who lived within. A slight noise made Silme’s head come up and her eyes searched the shadows but saw nothing. Yet the voice was clear and sharp, like daggers of ice, “Ah, the hope of the elven nation, the next Wielder of Lore, how perfect.”
<br />

<br />
Silmesse stood, eyes roving and finally alighted upon a pillar of shadow darker than the rest of the dim room. “Speak thy name, intruder. Thee hath visited upon a ceremony of secrecy and importance great.”
<br />

<br />
Dry rustling laughter, ‘Oh, forgiveness, little one. But it is you, and your kind who have invaded. You have continually hunted me, my slaves, and protected my prey. I tire of it. So, I seek to destroy your kind and to take you would do so,“ again laughter, “and as for my name wouldn’t one so wise know me?”
<br />

<br />
Her face, grim yet still lovely, was stern and fearless. Indeed she knew who was in her presence, The Slayer, he who had caused this empty castle, the one whom elven warriors sought nightly. Firm voiced, she answered, “Know thee I do, vile beast, The Slayer. Take me then, and the hunts for thee shall only intensify, another shall take my place, and you will destroy nothing.”
<br />

<br />
The tall shadow emerged, marble skinned and clad in sable, the Slayer looked down at her with dead black eyes. He hated yet lusted her beauty and strength. He pondered for a moment, knowing what she said was true and then he hit upon an idea, dark mirth flowed from him. “Take you? Yes, I shall, but not as I had planned, to keep you as food for a time, but to turn you. What better horror for an elf, lover of life and sun to become deadly and of the night? Once I have turned you, together we will wreak havoc upon your clan and YOU will destroy what once you loved and the elf nation will be as dust upon the wind.”
<br />

<br />
Even as Silme listened to his speech, she tried to run or cast a spell but his foul magick had bound her. As he came close, she saw the Shades there, powerless to act but bound by ceremony to give her, the Chosen, the knowledge. They would not appear for another 100 years.   Her mind absorbed the knowledge even as her body was drained of virtually all essence.
<br />

<br />
When she 'woke', the Slayer stood above her, her lifeblood still upon him. “Welcome little one, you shall call me Master and we will feed, but first a name, and it shall be Obsydyan, for your now dark beauty.”
<br />

<br />
She stood, fire and ice racing through her, hungering, and heard herself, “As Master wishes, may we feed now?"</span>
<br />

<br />
A wolf’s howl broke into her reverie. Obsydyan stripped her eyes from the pool, her anger and despair at falling into such memories made her long hunger all the more violent. She retreated from the Room of Pools, poisonously full of rage to wait for another to come, as they always had.<br />_________________<br /><img src="http://www.redaquarius.com/images/470_Taylah_sig.gif" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=42679" target="_blank" class="postlink">Tay's Slinkies</a>
