			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">CHAPTER 3: Fated Encounter (simba)
<br />

<br />
Then he was in the main hall of the castle. The outer part was ruinous, but it was obvious something, or someone, still walked these halls. There was neither dust nor webs. As Julian silently paced the different corridors he saw many pieces of elvish history; statues, paintings, and the like. Many were partially destroyed but most were intact - he found it odd that those in one piece were tucked into dark corners and niches. Why would that be?
<br />

<br />
At the end of a long hallway, he saw a door, but not of oak and this is what caught his attention. This door was huge, easily 8 feet high and made of heartwood. This in itself was amazing, heartwood was extinct. Long ago, there had been many but without elven magic, they had died. The wood was high gloss, incredibly durable, and deep red in hue, almost like blood. The door was also carved with runes and symbols, Julian had no idea what any of it meant but it was obviously a place of great meaning. He headed straight for it.
<br />

<br />
He stood in front of the door, admiring the skill and beauty of the carvings. Part of him didn’t expect to be able to open the massive door but when his hand lighted upon the silken finish, it swung noiselessly ajar. The room was huge. In the center of the room was a large pool, still and black. He began to walk towards it, and then stopped in complete dread. The thing or things that roamed here liked treasure of the most hideous sort. Where once torches had burned bright, now heads topped the stakes. There were probably a dozen total, three bearing the helmet still of the KingsGuard. As he gazed over the hideous line, his eyes fell on the final head, very fresh, as if placed only moments before he entered the room. It was Anderus, the young page of Sir Sicarius. 
<br />

<br />
Apparently, Anderus had followed him, hoping for riches and glory. This boy had never had a chance. Julian’s ire broke loose. He stormed about, cursing loudly and raging, unknowing that he was being watched by the same creature who performed this slaughter - and she was grinning.
<br />

<br />
When finally he got a hold on his emotions, he walked towards the pool, intending to wash the sweat from his brow. Instead he saw a tapestry that hung on the far wall. It was large, huge actually, and in perfect condition. Faces, objects, and places played upon the bright threads.
<br />

<br />
Julian was drawn to it and as he neared the hanging, he could see it was actually many scenes of a story of great importance. It covered the entire length of the wall. The Hunter looked over it and stopped at one section. A man’s face was there, rough, proud, and scarred. It was a handsome face, and also a face that bore great misery. The weaver had obviously known this man well. Perhaps the weaver had been the man himself but Julian thought he looked infinitely more a warrior than a crafter. He was awestruck - this couldn’t be. He couldn’t take his eyes from the man, the man who shared his face, and stood riveted for some time.
<br />

<br />
She watched him stand there, the mortal man whom had invaded her haven. She grinned when she watched his reaction to the young one’s demise. His death had been merited, he had entered on the man’s heels, and then when his eyes lit upon the many treasures, he had begun filling his knapsack. She had planned death for him and the other at any rate, but the plunder of her family’s treasures deserved special treatment. 
<br />

<br />
Now she planned to feed of this one as well, but she watched him for awhile, for some reason feeling as though they shared a common thread. She couldn't see how that would be, but the feeling stilled her for a time as she watched the handsome intruder. 
<br />

<br />
Suddenly the man turned from the wall hanging and strode to the pool, leaning down to stare at his own reflection. She laughed silently, mortals were so odd at times. In any case, his time for pondering the face of men was over. She glided forward, quieter than any cat, and stood behind him, looking into the pool over his shoulder. It took a moment for him to realize she was there. 
<br />

<br />
Julian whirled to face the Dark Lady. “I see the legends are true.” She tilted her head to the side, innocently, and began laughing girlishly. Her laughter was more chilling than anything else she could have done. He pulled his great sword from the scabbard yet made no move to attack her. Her laughter and her beauty held him still.
<br />

<br />
Finally she stopped yet her venomous, beautiful smile remained. “What do you here, mortal? Be ye in search of treasure? For that your friend perished - painfully and to my great delight.” Julian blanched, ire rising again, but made no move or answer. Her voice was surprisingly low, clear, and still held the musical lilt of the elven tongue. Again that girlish laughter and then she reached up and smacked him across the face, a ringing blow. 
<br />

<br />
Julian finally moved to rid the world of this foulness, yet even now as battle was joined, he refrained from a heavy offensive attack. He blocked and parried, needing all his considerable skill from her attack. She used only a staff for a weapon but it was more than enough in her strong hands. It was obvious she had trained as a warrior, her moves were skilled and deadly. He was lost in her graceful moves when he heard the low chant and realized she was spellcaster as well. He swore inwardly and began to invoke the wards against magick. She felt the ward knit itself and dropped the magicks, doubling her attack, but Julian felt she was toying with him.
<br />

<br />
As they fought she examined the man. He was brave, skilled, and fearless. She had never stood before any human who had not quailed at her laughter or fell to the floor, begging for mercy as though because she was lovely she was kind.  Kindness had been emptied from her along with her lifeblood. He was also handsome, for a human, incredibly so, and he evoked something deep inside her - within her elven soul. She found herself growing angry that he was confident (and that he had any effect on her)- she could tell he was not pressing his attack. In addition, he knew ward magick so she was unable to bind him still. 
<br />

<br />
Her green eyes began to flash and she saw that he interpreted it, a turn of events and not for good. Still he showed no fear. In fact, his defense was slowing. For a mere second it dropped, as though he was unable to decide what to do, and she grabbed him by the shoulders and threw him to the tapestry wall, her incredible physcial stength tossing him as she would a rag. As his body slammed into it, the stone underneath actually cracked. His limp form fell to the floor and she found it ironic that he landed beneath the tapestry picture of the Hunter from so long ago.
<br />

<br />
Julian landed hard, too hard. He felt broken inside and as he struggled to sit up, he coughed blood. She was walking slowly to him, knowing she had won. He could feel her kneel and he made a perfunctory effort at waving the great sword. She ignored it. He managed to sit up, somewhat, against the wall so he could again take in her face. She knelt there, looking like an angel. Julian wondered what that black mane of curls would feel like. Julian shook himself - what could he be thinking? This was evil incarnate - she must be destroyed somehow. She leaned in, close as a lover, and he knew he was through.
<br />

<br />
Against all odds, she stopped, her eyes went to slits at something behind him on the tapestry - perhaps she was mad he bled on it, he thought in his delirium? He could see her lips tighten and then her eyes looked to him, searching and finding something she didn’t like. “Ce’triel!, “ she hissed and backed a bit. He was startled to hear her speak elvish and was certain she had not meant to - her face showed that. He moved his sword minutely and her eyes went to it, widening slightly. He didn’t think she was suddenly worried about his use of the weapon and was instantly curious. 
<br />

<br />
Obsydyan was angry she had used her mother tongue for she had vowed never to tarnish anything elven again with her foulness. She was angrier however, at the man who was before her. “Thy name, pest?” she demanded.
<br />

<br />
His mouth moved to answer but it took a minute for any sound, “ I be….Julian..of…,” he broke into a bloody coughing fit and she waited with no pity on her face, “of… the Dawnslayer family.” Again she queried him, “What do you here, DawnSlayer?”
<br />

<br />
No coughing this time, but his voice was little more than whisper, “I have come to take the head of the demon that plagues this land with evil deeds, soul ravager.” Her face belied no expression at his words, and she bowed her head towards him fractionally.
<br />

<br />
Obsydyan knew his time was running out. The clear eyes were beginning to cloud. And she knew him and his family, although she was certain he had not connected everything yet. In fact she owed a ‘debt’ of sorts to one of his ancestors, the man in the tapestry - the Hunter whom had banished her to this castle. Fitting that his blood would now belong to her. She had planned to kill Julian, but as the mortals said, a “a favor begets a favor.” Now she would have a pretty new pet.  She grinned wolfishly. 
<br />

<br />
Julian’s eyes closed, his last strength was leaving him. He felt strangely satisfied, for though he had lost, he found a part of him felt blessed to have seen such loveliness, though it be clothed in evil. He felt he could die in peace and let go, but she had one more thing to say and her last words followed him into darkness, upsetting his peace. “You failed, Julian. What WOULD your ancestor say?” And that girlish, evil, …..enchanting laughter.<br />_________________<br /><img src="http://www.redaquarius.com/images/470_Taylah_sig.gif" border="0" />
<br />

