				<td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">CHAPTER FIVE - What Tangled Webs (simba)
<br />

<br />
She set the taper down on his bedside table and strode to the far side of the room. A frenetic energy seemed to pour from her. Julian tried to focus on her but even the guttering light of the candle was overly harsh to his newly sensitized eyes. He lay back and let her voice cover him, somehow soft as a kiss yet as clinging as a vine it came over him…
<br />

<br />
“I know of your family, and your lineage of being Vampire Hunters. I am sure you know wild tales handed down from your father or perhaps his father of me and my own. I am not here to play nursemaid and entertain you with tales of decadent horror. I am here to serve revenge and malice.”
<br />

<br />
With a bare whisper of fluid movement she was at his side on the darkened half of the room, where the candle threw shadows that grappled one another upon the walls. Later Julian would learn that she rarely entered the light; the shadows were as a lover to her, only they held her close and without fail. 
<br />

<br />
“Revenge?” he whispered, his voice rough from the fading pain. “I am not here for revenge, I came to serve justice upon you!” A brief flicker in his mind of the tapestry he had seen and he went silent.
<br />

<br />
She waved a slim hand, “Revenge on YOU and yours, lovely child. And don’t play coy, you lack the skill. I know you recognized your ancestor in my great Tapestry. Deny it not, I read you easily.” Again she melted back from his side, “You are descended from Llewyn Dawnslayer. You have his face…his build…his very <span style="font-style: italic">smell</span>.”
<br />

<br />
Julian slowly sat up, the pain was a distant memory, and his senses were blooming to their new potential. That is how he detected an odd note in her voice when she spoke of his thrice-great Grandfather. “Aye, I did, Lady. You are right.” He could see her outline now; she stood at a window across from him, facing out as she spoke…
<br />

<br />
“He came to wreak justice on me as well. He was smitten, as are you, by my face. It caused his weakness and my imprisonment. Things were different many moons ago, I knew less and more and so did he.” Julian frowned, his brow creased as he pondered that last statement.
<br />

<br />
Obsydyan sensed his confusion and her slight chuckle gave tell to it. “He came to slay me, Julian - I believe that is your term for justice. It was quite a battle. We fought for hours, spell and steel. He was…masterful. “ Yearning filled her tone, but dark and twisted. 
<br />

<br />
“He fell victim to my power of beauty and voice, the Dark Siren.” Julian actually smiled, he hadn’t heard that in years and at her utterance of it, he heard his beloved father’s voice telling him the tale of the Dark Siren so many years ago.
<br />

<br />
“Lady….” He got no further, she turned as he spoke and he was bound by her. She was bathed in the night’s radiance. The moonlight filtered thru the thick panes to form a nimbus of pale light behind her, setting her raven locks to glow eerily. Her eyes were shimmering orbs of green fire and her pale skin was bathed in starlight. She spoke low, “Do you see Julian? So little effort and you are as a bee in my web.”
<br />

<br />
He swallowed heavily, his eyes fixed upon her as a dying man’s upon his god would be. “Your Grandfather fell to his knees, at my feet, when I used my glamour on him. He begged, BEGGED, me to turn him and become my lover. It was really quite delicious.” She was at Julian’s side in an eyeblink, her hand under his chin and pulling his face up to look upon hers.
<br />

<br />
“Did I mention he begged?” A poisonous smile adorned her lips, a kiss of death upon them. Julian moaned, “No, no. He was brave, he was valiant, he would never be so weak!” And yet Julian himself did not resist her fierce grip or intoxicating closeness.
<br />

<br />
The poison in her smile grew, “Lies. You speak lies. How amusing.” She released him and retreated to her window. “He did beg, my slave. Pathetically. Only one thing saved him and it was not of his doing. It was mine.” 
<br />

<br />
She reached forth and pushed the window open into the ebony sky. A blast of air caused the candle to blank out yet Julian found he could see her perfectly now. “Dawn came Julian. We had battled that long. We had played, danced, it was like a lover’s courtship our battle. And overlong had it gone. I erred, Bloodkin. I waited so long, too long and with the dawn my full glamour faded and I retreated to the darkness, weakened, driven to my rest.”
<br />

<br />
The knight looked towards the window, full dark still. “But I am turned, Lady?” 
<br />

<br />
“Aye so ye are. With you, I did not court.....much. I took. I have learned much since your grandfather. And to end my tale, when came the dawn, precious to so many, he regained…something of his senses. He cast great magicks over my castle, binding me here as a spider in her web so that only my prey may come to me, but I may not hunt them.” Venom and something else …(thankfulness??) ..deep down filled her emotions. Julian wondered…
<br />

<br />
“So I have been so many years. And now, I can use you - his kin, my slave - to resume my hunt and bring prizes to me, your Mistress.” Silence pervaded the room for a time as she ended her tale and Julian pondered it. 
<br />

<br />
Finally he spoke, “Lady, you lost no glamour. You are beauty twisted. My ancestor did exact justice well. To keep you ‘alive’, to each day remember the sweetness of the air when you were Silmesse, and also to keep you from enjoying the hunt of being Obsydyan. No better punishment could he have done. It is fitting.” He had goaded her intentionally, perhaps seeking a release from her justice...
<br />

<br />
He expected anger, punishment and instead received a reply as emotionless as a corpse, “I agree. And yet he could have killed me as the sun birthed and he did not. He knew deaths would still fall for ever are there seekers of treasure in castles old and they would be as lambs to my slaughter, those who entered. He bound me here yet insured my sustenance for when he left, tales sprang up of glory and riches here. Who told those Julian? None afore he had survived a visit here. He was superbly weak and terribly strong, he was righteous and he was evil. How do you explain his justice now, fallen Slayer?”
<br />

<br />
With that she opened the door of his chamber and was gone before he could form a reply. Not that Julian had one ready. He laid back, pondering all that he knew of her history and of his great great great grandfather’s. He didn’t even notice the servant, once a KingsGuard now magickally bound to Obsydyan, who came in to close a thick curtain over his window, blocking the coming of the sun, nor the carafe of deep red wine and the goblet he placed at his bedside table. Julian was lost in his thoughts and as dawn came, he never even thought to end it all by opening the curtain and letting the sun cleanse and destroy him. 
<br />

<br />
As the sun breached the horizon, he slept as he Awakened. 
<br />

<br />
CHAPTER 6 - Memory (Simba)
<br />

<br />
Enough, she thought, I told him enough. He will chew on it and the snippets and tales he has heard will come forth. He will piece it together. Julian did not need to know of the final scene, she had no desire to exploit her weakness.  Obsydyan disappeared into the bowels of the Keep, avoiding the light as she had for so long.  
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">Llewyn Dawnslayer. Once he had been great but the townsfolk knew what he had encountered in that castle had ravaged him in some way. Or thought they knew. He was everything he had been still yet he was now also a man in love and full of self-loathing for it. How could he love such foulness, even now?
<br />

<br />
But he did. It was not only her glamour; that had broke at the whisper of dawn. She was lovely afore and after the glamour had covered her. When the glamour was in full flower, she was exquisite; painful to look at almost. But it was more than that. Something in her called to him. Perhaps it was the elven blood in him, slight though it was. He knew not what nor in fact, cared. He only knew that his love was true, if not pure.
<br />

<br />
He could not bear to kill her and so confined her and wept after he told tales to greedy adventurers, knowing they would come back nevermore from that castle. But he did it for he could not bear to be without her, even if he could not be at her side.
<br />

<br />
Years passed and he came to know his death was near. Llewyn Dawnslayer returned to that dark castle, never seen again by the town. He wished to die at her hands, her face the last thing he saw, her laughter carrying him into oblivion. He begged for it. This time, she complied. </span>
<br />

<br />
Obsydyan reached her chamber, her mind roiling with the memory of taking Llewyn's lifesblood, holding him close to her as tears escaped his shut lids, and her final words to him...
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">"Kaim, aratoamin. Lle ume quel. Diola lle."</span><br />_________________<br /><img src="http://www.redaquarius.com/images/470_Taylah_sig.gif" border="0" />
